1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,019
Most of us would prefer to sip and savor good wine, not wheel and deal in it.

2
00:00:08,019 --> 00:00:13,439
But wine is fast becoming an increasingly sought after alternative investment.

3
00:00:13,439 --> 00:00:16,399
So maybe I shouldn't have even opened it.

4
00:00:16,399 --> 00:00:21,760
After all, who knows how much it might be worth in three years or even 30.

5
00:00:21,760 --> 00:00:27,839
This month, two auction houses, Christie's and Dobia Shovtsky held wine auctions in Switzerland

6
00:00:27,839 --> 00:00:33,840
and a new wine storage space, a kind of wine cellar meets bank opened in Laupern.

7
00:00:33,840 --> 00:00:40,240
We visited Dobia Shovtsky in Bern, which sold all of the 1,000 bottles it was offering in auction.

8
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:45,200
Most of the bordeaux and burgundies, the most coveted wines worldwide.

9
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:53,679
One of the highlights was a bottle of Romane Conti Grand Gru from 1986 estimated at 6,000 Swiss francs

10
00:00:53,679 --> 00:00:56,000
but sold for 10,000.

11
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,439
That introduced me to you.

12
00:00:59,439 --> 00:01:05,359
Let's say I would buy a bottle for 8,000 and I see this as an investment.

13
00:01:05,359 --> 00:01:14,079
Is there a certain time-raged or duration that I have to keep this investment in order for it to be profitable?

14
00:01:14,079 --> 00:01:22,079
I think it's in nature of every passion investment that it's a long-term investment.

15
00:01:22,159 --> 00:01:30,640
You might have a market chance to sell it very quickly but usually you hold it and you wait for the market chance.

16
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:38,640
When you go to a passion investment, it's absolutely crucial that you make your homework.

17
00:01:38,640 --> 00:01:43,439
You have to educate yourself, you have to educate the big knowledge.

18
00:01:43,439 --> 00:01:49,439
If you just buy randomly any wine, any watch, you will never have any profit.

19
00:01:49,519 --> 00:01:54,480
In every market it's the blue chips, it's the 1% that makes the difference.

20
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:58,719
So you as an auction house you've been selling wine for a while already

21
00:01:58,719 --> 00:02:04,159
but why is it important to not just offer art or watches but to diversify?

22
00:02:04,159 --> 00:02:14,159
There are so many fields that have been traditional collection fields like antiquities, 19th century paintings

23
00:02:14,799 --> 00:02:18,079
that they're just dying and disappearing.

24
00:02:18,079 --> 00:02:25,120
So for an auction house it's crucial to find other collectibles that replace this

25
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:31,439
and collectibles like wine, watches is fantastic because you have a global market for it.

26
00:02:31,439 --> 00:02:38,800
If you have a pottec philippe, you have bias from China to Russia, from Switzerland to Norway.

27
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:43,439
Everybody is interested. Same to the wine, it's a fantastic field

28
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:46,319
to open the market internationally.

29
00:02:46,319 --> 00:02:51,199
So once you bought a decent bottle of wine, the question arises of where to store it.

30
00:02:51,199 --> 00:02:53,039
And I'm here with Nikola Stemfle.

31
00:02:53,039 --> 00:02:56,879
Your family has been in the wine business since 1904.

32
00:02:56,879 --> 00:02:59,680
So I wonder why did you open a wine bank now?

33
00:02:59,680 --> 00:03:05,599
We found out that people do not have enough space for the storage of wine.

34
00:03:06,240 --> 00:03:11,439
So we wanted to give them the opportunity to store the wines really properly

35
00:03:11,520 --> 00:03:14,719
and in the perfect climate-sized cellar.

36
00:03:23,680 --> 00:03:30,639
We have the perfect temperature. It's between 14.5 and 16 degrees constantly.

37
00:03:31,199 --> 00:03:35,680
And also we have 75 to 85 degree humidity.

38
00:03:36,480 --> 00:03:45,280
And it's actually a huge, a huge wine storage fridge.

39
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:51,439
The compoundings they have from 70 bottles roughly to 1500 bottles capacity.

40
00:03:51,439 --> 00:03:53,920
So a total of how many 30,000 bottles?

41
00:03:53,920 --> 00:03:54,719
30,000 bottles.

42
00:03:54,719 --> 00:03:55,600
Could be stored here.

43
00:03:55,600 --> 00:03:56,080
Here, here.

44
00:03:56,879 --> 00:04:04,240
Here we have a size M where we have space for roughly 240, 300 bottles.

45
00:04:04,240 --> 00:04:04,560
Okay.

46
00:04:05,360 --> 00:04:09,920
And here we have size XS.

47
00:04:10,479 --> 00:04:11,039
XS?

48
00:04:11,039 --> 00:04:15,199
So you have XS, M, L and XL.

49
00:04:15,199 --> 00:04:15,680
Okay.

50
00:04:15,680 --> 00:04:17,759
And how much would you pay for XS?

51
00:04:17,759 --> 00:04:21,040
XS, it's 150 francs per year.

52
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:26,480
And the most expensive is the one for 1500, 1600 bottles for 900 francs per year.

53
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:27,279
Which is behind you.

54
00:04:27,279 --> 00:04:28,240
Which is behind me, yes.

55
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:29,040
Which is free.

56
00:04:29,040 --> 00:04:32,720
You can actually let cases deliver here.

57
00:04:32,800 --> 00:04:36,480
And we're going to put it in the locker or you can let it send.

58
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:39,280
You can buy wine via us.

59
00:04:39,280 --> 00:04:40,960
And we store it here directly.

60
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:44,880
You can sell wine via us.

61
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:51,120
So actually we really wanted to have a really transactional kind of storage here.

62
00:04:51,120 --> 00:04:56,000
We can all combine that via an app that we programmed.

63
00:04:56,160 --> 00:05:00,639
We build with memory.

64
00:05:00,639 --> 00:05:04,240
Investing in wine seems to be a bit of a trend.

65
00:05:05,199 --> 00:05:08,879
But compared to other assets, it doesn't really, doesn't pay dividend.

66
00:05:09,839 --> 00:05:12,240
Investors have to pay for storage.

67
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:17,279
And it requires some time until you can liquidate a collection of wine,

68
00:05:17,279 --> 00:05:19,360
which is maybe four or five months or so.

69
00:05:19,360 --> 00:05:22,079
So there are some disadvantages why I still do it.

70
00:05:22,159 --> 00:05:26,399
Investing in wine should be considered really as a passion asset.

71
00:05:26,399 --> 00:05:34,159
So it is one asset class that is just not buns or shares or real estate.

72
00:05:34,159 --> 00:05:37,039
So should consider it as a passion asset.

73
00:05:37,039 --> 00:05:38,560
That's the first thing.

74
00:05:38,560 --> 00:05:44,319
And then it is really important to know that it's very volatile investing in wine.

75
00:05:46,479 --> 00:05:51,680
It should never be your primary investment.

76
00:05:51,759 --> 00:05:52,879
Why is it so volatile?

77
00:05:53,759 --> 00:05:58,240
It is volatile because demands change quite quickly.

78
00:05:58,959 --> 00:06:00,959
Scores of critics change.

79
00:06:00,959 --> 00:06:02,560
That's a price driver.

80
00:06:03,840 --> 00:06:09,360
Different factor really changed the price of a bottle or a case of wine.

81
00:06:10,240 --> 00:06:15,360
Over the past 10 years, the prices for fine wine have gone through some significant swings.

82
00:06:15,360 --> 00:06:19,280
Philippe Mazette, professor at the School of Hospitality in Luzanne,

83
00:06:19,279 --> 00:06:22,559
says that starting in mid 2009, for instance,

84
00:06:22,559 --> 00:06:25,839
prices increased thanks to new customers from China,

85
00:06:25,839 --> 00:06:31,759
as well as the beginning of the economic recovery before the market corrected in mid 2011.

86
00:06:31,759 --> 00:06:34,959
As Mazette says from a pure investment standpoint,

87
00:06:34,959 --> 00:06:39,359
fine wines retained the advantage of being only weekly correlated with stocks

88
00:06:39,359 --> 00:06:42,799
and therefore offer significant diversification potential.

89
00:06:43,439 --> 00:06:49,759
So if I want to invest in wine and have some profit,

90
00:06:49,759 --> 00:06:52,800
when would it make sense to sell it again?

91
00:06:53,840 --> 00:06:58,560
So we consider three to seven years.

92
00:06:58,560 --> 00:07:00,560
And if it's a really collectible bottle,

93
00:07:01,759 --> 00:07:05,759
a really rare bottle, you can still sell it in 20, 30 years.

94
00:07:06,399 --> 00:07:08,319
It pays a...

95
00:07:09,279 --> 00:07:14,879
It gains a normally on value because it's getting rare and rare over the time,

96
00:07:14,879 --> 00:07:18,319
because still people still drink the wine.

97
00:07:18,319 --> 00:07:19,680
So...

98
00:07:19,680 --> 00:07:21,519
Is it still drinkable after 30 years?

99
00:07:22,399 --> 00:07:25,120
Yes, yes, there are wines that are really delicious.

100
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:28,159
But of course you need to have the clientele

101
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:33,039
and the clients really to enjoy those wines.

102
00:07:33,039 --> 00:07:34,399
And I think it's very important

103
00:07:35,839 --> 00:07:38,000
if you consider wine as investment,

104
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:43,039
then I think you, as a person, you still should be interested in the wine itself.

105
00:07:44,480 --> 00:07:49,759
And I think at the end, you should love the wines too.

106
00:07:49,759 --> 00:07:54,480
And I think that's then going to be a really nice passion as it.

107
00:07:54,480 --> 00:07:57,920
So you mentioned in the beginning at least three to seven years.

108
00:07:59,439 --> 00:08:01,439
Why this time span?

109
00:08:02,319 --> 00:08:05,920
So actually when wines are getting released from the winery,

110
00:08:06,639 --> 00:08:09,759
in the first, let's say, two years,

111
00:08:10,719 --> 00:08:19,360
the aroma's flavors and the brand and the image of the wine is maybe not formed 100%.

112
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:23,199
So after time of, let's say, three to seven years,

113
00:08:23,199 --> 00:08:25,040
you have more critics scores.

114
00:08:25,839 --> 00:08:28,480
The wine is quite ready to go.

115
00:08:28,720 --> 00:08:33,680
And so the bottle's getting rarer and rarer.

116
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:38,480
And you see there actually if you can make profit out of the wine or not.

117
00:08:38,480 --> 00:08:40,639
And I think it's the most important time

118
00:08:41,519 --> 00:08:44,000
to see where the bottle goes.

119
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,360
I mean where the prices are going.

120
00:08:45,920 --> 00:08:47,279
What defines a price?

121
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:53,120
The price of a wine is defined by quality, of course.

122
00:08:53,759 --> 00:08:54,639
What does that mean?

123
00:08:54,639 --> 00:08:56,320
Yeah, that's a good question.

124
00:08:56,800 --> 00:09:01,680
And the taste simply the taste, the ripeness,

125
00:09:02,960 --> 00:09:06,320
the balance, the overall quality of the wine.

126
00:09:06,320 --> 00:09:08,720
And then you have price drivers like the brand,

127
00:09:08,720 --> 00:09:12,320
from whom is it produced, the shattered, the producer,

128
00:09:15,280 --> 00:09:20,480
the quality, the storage quality, the labels, how nice the labels are.

129
00:09:20,480 --> 00:09:23,600
So if the label is like scratch, it loses a lot of value?

130
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:28,879
Yeah, not a lot, but it's still losing a little bit of value because people that want to buy the bottle,

131
00:09:28,879 --> 00:09:30,320
they want to have pristine bottles.

132
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:32,080
They want to have really nice bottles.

133
00:09:32,080 --> 00:09:34,720
So you mentioned quality, the ripeness.

134
00:09:34,720 --> 00:09:39,759
I'm just thinking now of the impact that maybe climate change has.

135
00:09:39,759 --> 00:09:41,440
Do you see an impact?

136
00:09:41,440 --> 00:09:42,639
Yes, it has an impact.

137
00:09:43,759 --> 00:09:50,000
We see way higher degrees of alcohol than we saw 10 years ago even.

138
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:55,279
It's shifting from 13 to now 15.5.

139
00:09:55,279 --> 00:09:58,000
So I need to drink less to feel something?

140
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:00,320
Yes, that's true.

141
00:10:00,320 --> 00:10:07,919
And also that's also a problem because the consumption is going down from year to year

142
00:10:07,919 --> 00:10:10,000
and we have statistics from it.

143
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,919
But the volume on the general market is actually growing.

144
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:21,919
But what we see also is a shift from cheaper bottles to rather more expensive bottles of wine.

145
00:10:21,919 --> 00:10:22,879
Okay.

146
00:10:22,879 --> 00:10:23,919
That's an interesting shift.

147
00:10:24,479 --> 00:10:26,559
Can you comment that?

148
00:10:26,559 --> 00:10:31,599
I think that people, if they're drinking a bottle of wine in the evening or on the weekends,

149
00:10:32,240 --> 00:10:37,120
they rather take something quite good and just cheap plunk.

150
00:10:37,120 --> 00:10:41,679
And climate change besides having an impact on the alcohol degree,

151
00:10:42,479 --> 00:10:44,719
it also has an impact on story.

152
00:10:44,719 --> 00:10:45,599
Yes, exactly.

153
00:10:45,599 --> 00:10:48,399
So what we see also is that I mean,

154
00:10:48,399 --> 00:10:50,559
summers are getting longer and longer.

155
00:10:50,559 --> 00:10:53,439
And even in those in the old buildings,

156
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,319
the sellers take a heat and up,

157
00:10:57,439 --> 00:11:00,479
which is not very good for storing the wines.

158
00:11:00,479 --> 00:11:05,599
So that was also one of the reasons why we actually build up the seller here.

159
00:11:05,599 --> 00:11:07,439
We're talking about passion investments,

160
00:11:08,240 --> 00:11:12,400
but you can also have wine as a speculative investment.

161
00:11:12,400 --> 00:11:15,760
Beculative wines is a big topic.

162
00:11:16,960 --> 00:11:23,200
Some brands profit from very good critics' scores or from a brand recognition that's

163
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:24,240
worldwide known.

164
00:11:25,200 --> 00:11:28,320
Lafitte Rochard, for example, is quite a speculative wine.

165
00:11:30,640 --> 00:11:34,480
And then you have volatility on those prices.

166
00:11:34,879 --> 00:11:37,680
How much is that specific Rochard bottle?

167
00:11:37,680 --> 00:11:43,680
It's around 850, 750 to 850 francs, it depends on the market.

168
00:11:43,680 --> 00:11:46,159
And then how does it work to whom do you sell it to?

169
00:11:47,120 --> 00:11:50,480
So we actually sell it on a very old school way.

170
00:11:50,480 --> 00:11:52,080
We sell it via email.

171
00:11:52,960 --> 00:11:56,800
We also have a website where we list all the wines of our clients.

172
00:11:57,600 --> 00:12:02,240
So people worldwide can check the lists and if they find something interesting,

173
00:12:02,240 --> 00:12:05,600
they can order it online or via email.

174
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:11,120
And we send out some offers and people react or they don't react.

175
00:12:11,120 --> 00:12:13,039
And if they don't react, the price is too high.

176
00:12:13,039 --> 00:12:13,759
It's very easy.

177
00:12:13,759 --> 00:12:15,759
And who buys these kind of bottles?

178
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:24,960
In this case, in this particular case, we have people from the Asian region.

179
00:12:24,960 --> 00:12:31,360
We have people from London, which is a big place of fine wine.

180
00:12:31,360 --> 00:12:33,519
It's a big marketplace of fine wines.

181
00:12:33,519 --> 00:12:39,840
Those are very specific markets for brands that really work in these kind of markets.

182
00:12:39,840 --> 00:12:43,279
So it's less about what you would see in your local wine bank?

183
00:12:44,399 --> 00:12:46,639
Yeah, it's less about what we would see here.

184
00:12:46,639 --> 00:12:51,279
Just to wrap it up, what kind of advice can you give to someone that wants to invest in wine?

185
00:12:51,279 --> 00:12:59,759
To invest in upcoming producers or in underrated producers, upcoming regions,

186
00:12:59,759 --> 00:13:02,399
underrated winetages.

187
00:13:02,399 --> 00:13:08,559
To invest in wine that you really like and to find out which one you like, you need to taste it.

188
00:13:10,159 --> 00:13:16,879
For Cine, Monizuotaland, I'm Tani König, Chin Chin.
